The Heliophysics Integrated Observatory (HELIO: http://www.helio-vo.eu ) is a virtual observatory dedicated to the solar physics and heliophysics (Bentley et al.

Especially, the Heliospheric Feature Catalogue (HFC: http://voparis-helio.obspm.fr/hfc-gui/index.php ) is a database- oriented service that allows access to a large amount of solar and heliospheric features data.

In particular, Gao, Wang, and Zhou (2002) have tracked lament disappearances over a full year, and the code of Bernasconi, Rust, and Hakim (2005) is currently applied to detect and track laments on Big Bear Solar Observatory (BBSO) images, providing among others data to the Heliophysics Events Knowledgebase (HEK: http://lmsal.com/hek/ ).
More than fteen years of data are accessible from the BASS2000 website ( http://bass2000.obspm.fr/home.php ), which permits us to apply the tracking algorithm over a large period of time.

We use here an algorithm developed in the framework of the European Grid of Solar Observations (EGSO: http://www.egso.org ) project, and successfully applied on H data from the Meudon Spectroheliograph and BBSO (Fuller, Aboudarham, and Bentley, 2005).

Flatau University of California San Diego Scripps Institution of Oceanography La Jolla CA 92093-0221 (pflatau@ucsd.edu ) last revised: 2012 May 14 Abstract DDSCAT 7.2 is a freely available open-source Fortran-90 software package applying the ‚Äúdiscrete dipole approximation‚Äù (DDA) to calculate scattering and absorption of electromagnetic waves by targets with arbitrary geometries and complex refractive index.
Up-to-date information on DDSCAT can be found at http://code.google.com/p/ddscat/ The latest version of DDSCAT 7.2 can be found at this URL.
Finally, the current version of this User Guide can be obtained from http://arxiv.org/abs/1202.3424 .

More informa- tion on how to do this can be found at http://code.google.com/p/ddscat The remainder of this section will assume that the installation is taking place on a Unix, Linux or Mac OSX system with the standard developer tools (e.g., tar,make , and a f90 or f95 compiler) installed.

Then by following the approach proposed in [5], DMuses the following Datalog rules to produce IRIsfor classes and data type properties: CLASSIRI(R,X)‚ÜêCLASS(R),CONCAT 2(base,R,X) DTP_IRI (A,R,X)‚ÜêDTP(A,R),CONCAT 4(base,R,"#",A,X) For instance, http://example.edu/db/STUDENT is the IRI for the STUDENT relation in our example, and http://example.edu/db/STUDENT#NAME is the IRI for attribute NAMEin the STUDENT relation (recall that DTP("NAME","STUDENT" )holds in our example).

First, for object properties ge nerated from binary relations,the following rules isused: OP_IRI 1(R,A,B,S,C,T,D,X )‚Üê BINREL(R,A,B,S,C,T,D ), CONCAT 10(base,R,"#",A,",",B,",",C,",",D,X) Thus,http://example.edu/db/ENROLLED#SID,CID,SID,CID is the IRI for binary relation ENROLLED in our example.

Second, for object properties generated from a foreign key consisti ng ofn attributes(n‚â•1), the followingrule isused: OP_IRI 2n(X1,...,X n,Y1,...,Y n,S,T,X)‚Üê OP2n(X1,...,X n,Y1,...,Y n,S,T), CONCAT 4n+4(base,S,",",T,"#",X1,",",...,X n‚àí1,",", Xn,",",Y1,",",...,Y n‚àí1,",",Yn,X) Thus, given that OP 2("CODE", "DID", "COURSE" ,"DEPT")holds in our example, IRI http://example.edu/db/COURSE,DEPT#CODE,DID is generated to represented the fact that CODEis a foreign key in the tableCOURSE thatreferences attribute DIDinthe table DEPT.

4.4.1 GeneratingIRIs fortuples We introduce a family of predicates that produce IRIs for the tuples being translated, where we assume a given a base IRI basefor the relational database (for example, "http://example.edu/db/" ).

First,DMuses the follow- ingDatalogruletoproduce IRIsforthe tuplesof therelatio ns hav- inga primary key: ROWIRIn(V1,V2,...,V n,A1,A2,...,A n,T,R,X )‚Üê PKn(A1,A2,...,A n,R),VALUE(V1,A1,T,R), VALUE(V2,A2,T,R),...,VALUE(Vn,An,T,R), CONCAT 4n+2(base,R,"#",A1,"=",V1,",", A2,"=",V2,",",...,",",An,"=",Vn,X) Thus, given that the facts PK 1("SID","STUDENT" )and VALUE("1","SID","id1","STUDENT" )holdinourexample, the IRI http://example.edu/db/STUDENT#SID=1 is the identiÔ¨Åer for the tuple in table STUDENT with value 1in the pri- marykey.

Predicate H ASPKnis deÔ¨Åned by the following n rules: HASPKn(X)‚ÜêPKi(A1,...,A i,X)i‚àà{1,...,n} The followingrule generates the table triples: TRIPLE(U,"rdf:type" ,W)‚Üê VALUE(V,A,T,R ),TUPLEID(T,R,U),CLASSIRI(R,W) Forexample, the followingis a table tripleinour example: TRIPLE("http://example.edu/db/STUDENT#SID=1" , "rdf:type" , "http://example.edu/db/STUDENT" ) Forreferencetriples, DMgeneratestriplesthatstorethereferences generated by binary relations and foreign keys.

Hybrid chains, substitution processes which vary across the tree, are discussed briey in the section on \Recent enhancements to XRate", and the details of their specication is thoroughly covered in the XRate format documentation, available here: http://biowiki.org/XrateFormat .

XDecoder is available as an XRate grammar, linked here: http://biowiki.org/XratePaper2011 Motivation for implementation Our endeavor to re-implement the RNADecoder grammar was based both on practical and methodological reasons.

The details of specifying such models are contained within the XRate format documentation, at http://biowiki.org/XrateFormat Ancestral sequence reconstruction A phylo-grammar is a generative model: it generates a hidden parse tree, then further generates observed data conditional on that parse tree.
